product_name: Image Kills Nutsedge Ready-to-Spray
review_text: I had the worst case of Poa Annua, weeds, and bare spots in Bermuda grass imaginable to the point I thought about tearing it out and re-sodding. This product worked great, but you have to monitor the coverage. I started by spraying with a hose attached bottle that did not meter out coverage correctly. I had to spray the area 4 or 5 times to get the right amount to product out of the bottle. The hose attachment seemed to work fine at first then slowed down dispensing product. I did a second spray 2 weeks later with another bottle again moving slowly and recovering area 4 - 5 times until the correct amount was dispensed. Finally, 3 to 4 weeks later, I followed up with a pump sprayer to spot treat a few survivors (still took 6 gals of spray). 3 weeks later I spread 10/10/10 fertilizer followed by 32/0/10 after another 3 weeks. Now I have the best results ever. So, the trick is treating the area several times making sure to use the correct amount and give it some time. If you have your own hose type sprayer, you may be better off buying the liquid and mixing your own batch to assure correct spread instead of using their defective hose bottle. I wish I took a "before picture" but you can see the results after a few months.

As a safety precaution: wear eye protection esp. if youre unfamiliar with the setup.I like the fact that there are no "jaws" that snap or hinge, which allows you to place this trap in more enclosed areas. Also, this is safer with my pet dog around since she cant step on it and have her paw get snapped.This traps tube opening limits the size of the catch - so if the rodent cant fit inside the tube, then it wont get caught. review_title: It grew grass where grass never grows...will it last?
review_text: I have an area in my backyard that hasnt had grass for several years. It is the first 20 or so feet next to my house, under a large tree, and next to my deck. The area gets almost no direct sunlight in the summer and the grass had died and been replaced by moss.  This year I killed the moss, dug it out and disposed of it, tilled up the area, and then brought in 2 yard of new clean dirt.  I used this dense shade mix because even before the moss I had never been able to grow enough grass to get it to hold.  Typically after a few weeks I had less than 50% coverage and by 8 weeks all the grass had died again.  This year I have gotten over 80% coverage after about 3 weeks and I went ahead and overseeded with another bag!  I am so happy with the coverage right now as you can see in the photo. I will add the caveat that this could all end up dying, but the results so far are not only positive, but are in another league compared to my past efforts.  If this grass holds all year I will be over seeding with this again in the future!Great product that worked wonderfully to at least begin growing for me!

product_name: Pennington Smart Patch Dense Shade Mix, 5 lb Jug
review_text: I admit, my lawn is not the greatest.  There are multiple bare spots which require repair, so I thought I would try this Pennington patch mix.  Its an interesting product - a mix of seed, mulch, fertilizer, and ... a tackifier.  This last item was new to me.  Pennington adds something that helps keep the seed from being washed away by rainfall, especially on slopes and hills.  It hasnt rained since I applied the seed, so I cant comment on how well it works, but I sure like the idea.  You cant imagine how many times rain has washed seed off my lawn.  I applied the mix by hand - its granules of mulch with seed and fertilizer mixed in - easy to apply where needed.  The seed itself is a fescue blend which is claimed to sprout in as little as 5 days (thats pretty quick), and I am pretty sure that all the seed is perennial.  Per the ingredient listing, the mix also has soil amendments (microbes).  It seems to me that Pennington has put everything they know about growing grass into this mix.  There are even online video instructions, if you would rather learn that way.  I think this is really going to help improve my lawn.

product_name: Pennington Smart Patch Dense Shade Mix, 5 lb Jug
review_text: Pennington 10 lbs. Smart Patch Tall Fescue Grass Seed with Mulch, Fertilizer. I prepared an area approximately 200 square feet as recommended on the package. I loosened the soil and added a bag of topsoil for good measure. I spread the seed, fertilizer and mulch mixture over the area by hand and then lightly raked the mixture into the topsoil. I covered the area with a light sprinkling of straw to protect the seed and hold moisture. Then I watered two times a day. The ryegrass mixture is advertised to show growth after as little as five days with full growth showing by 14 days. Ryegrass is often used as a cover while the permanent seed develops and after a few months depending on moisture the ryegrass will turn brown and die off. The package does not state the percentage of ryegrass seed just the four varieties of Fescue. There is a map of the US showing the best areas of the country for this product. Southern most states including my state of Florida are not in the idea zone so it will be interesting to see how the seed and grass do in this climate region. The 10-pound bag is advertised as a smart patch system to repair dead patches in your yard. Pennington guaranties the seed to grow and asks for feedback if the product does not perform as advertised. After watering twice a day, on the 5th day I could see sprouts of green poking up through the dirt. Two days later there were clumps of green visible but not evenly spread. The first spread was thinner than as I moved down the area and it could be that the seed was not evenly distributed in the bag.
